<subsection xml:id="subsec-angles-in-a-straight-line">
    <title>Angles in a Straight Line</title>
    <p>
        An angle on a straight line refers to two or more angles that are formed along a straight path. 
        The key property of angles on a straight line is that their sum always adds up to <m>180^\circ</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        If two angles are placed next to each other on a straight line, they are called <term>supplementary angles</term> (they add up to <m>180^\circ</m>)
    </p>
    <p>
        If a line is split into two angles, you can always find the missing angle by subtracting the known angle from 180°.
    </p>
    <p>
        Examples of angles in a straight line in real life include:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    A flat table surface forming a straight <m>180^\circ</m> angle.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The edge of a notebook when opened completely.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The angle formed by the hour and the minute hands of a clock when it points at <m>6:00.</m> 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
